"""
mkt-context | Leviticus | chapters 5–7
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-leviticus-5-7-fill.py

Ch 5: Graduated sin offering (chatat) — three liability categories (oath, impurity,
       rash vow); sliding scale for the poor; asham for sacrilege with chomesh surcharge.
Ch 6: Priestly rubrics for asham (interpersonal torts), tamid fire, grain offering
       (minchah), sin offering portions — the altar fire that must never go out.
Ch 7: Asham distribution, peace offering categories (toda/neder/nadavah) with time
       limits, fat/blood prohibition, wave offering (tenupha) priestly portions;
       closing summary of all five sacrifice types.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>If anyone sins in that he hears a public adjuration (<em>qol alah</em>) to testify and though he is a witness, whether he has seen or come to know the matter, yet does not speak — the <em>qol alah</em> (voice/announcement of an oath) is a formal public summons to witnesses to come forward in a legal proceeding; failure to testify when one has relevant knowledge creates a specific category of communal guilt (<em>avon</em>). The obligation to testify truthfully is foundational in the ancient Israelite legal system (Exod 20:16; 23:1-3), and non-testimony is here treated as a legal and cultic offense requiring atonement.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Or if anyone touches any unclean thing, whether a carcass of an unclean wild animal or a carcass of unclean livestock or a carcass of unclean swarming things (<em>sheqetz</em>), even though he does not know it — unintentional contact with animal carcasses (Lev 11 defines the clean/unclean taxonomy) creates culpability even when the person was unaware at the time. The concept of inadvertent defilement (<em>nefesh ki tiggah</em>) reflects an understanding that impurity has objective effects regardless of subjective intention, a feature of Israelite purity theology that distinguishes it from moral-intent-based systems like the Roman <em>mens rea</em> framework.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Or if he touches human uncleanness, of whatever sort the uncleanness may be, with which one becomes unclean (<em>tum'at adam</em>), and it is hidden from him — human impurity sources (corpse, discharge, skin disease) are distinguished from animal impurity sources (v.2); <em>tum'at adam</em> encompasses the full range of Lev 11–15 human impurity categories. The formula <em>vene'elam mimenu</em> (it was hidden from him) is the technical term for the unwitting aspect of these violations throughout Lev 4–5.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Or if anyone utters with his lips a rash oath (<em>nishba levatte bisetafayim</em>) to do evil or to do good, any sort of rash oath that people swear, and it is hidden from him — the rash oath (<em>shevuat shav</em>) is an impulsive, unconsidered verbal commitment later forgotten; the inclusion of oaths to do good (not only harmful oaths) indicates that the culpability is in the making-and-forgetting rather than in the content. The pairing 'evil or good' creates a merism covering all possible oath content.</p>",
    "5": "<p>When he becomes guilty in any of these, he shall confess the sin he has committed (<em>ve-hitvaddah asher chata aleiha</em>) — the confession requirement (<em>viduy</em>) precedes the offering; the ritual alone without acknowledgment of specific wrongdoing is insufficient. Confession before sacrifice is a distinctive feature of Israelite atonement theology; in Mesopotamian ritual texts (Marduk-šum-uṣur incantations, namburbi rituals) the verbal component exists but is typically addressed to deities in third person rather than first-person confession of specific acts.</p>",
    "6": "<p>He shall bring to YHWH as his compensation for the sin that he has committed, a female from the flock, a lamb or a goat, for a sin offering (<em>chatat</em>); and the priest shall make atonement for him for his sin — the standard <em>chatat</em> for these three categories is a female animal (contrast the male animal required for leaders and priests in Lev 4:3,22-23). The female animal represents the base-level offering for individual lay Israelites; the graduated scale that follows (vv.7-13) accommodates economic inability to provide even this.</p>",
    "7": "<p>But if he cannot afford a lamb (<em>im lo taggiya yado dei she</em>), then he shall bring to YHWH as his compensation for the sin that he has committed two turtledoves or two pigeons (<em>shtei torim o shtei vnei yona</em>) — the sliding scale begins: those who cannot afford a sheep bring two birds instead. This graduated provision for the poor is one of the most distinctive features of the Levitical offering system; no comparable sliding scale appears in Mesopotamian temple records from Ur III or Old Babylonian periods, where temple offerings were largely fixed by professional category and social rank.</p>",
    "8": "<p>And he shall bring them to the priest, who shall offer first the one for the sin offering (<em>chatat</em>). He shall wring its head from its neck but shall not sever it completely (<em>malaq et-rosho mimul orfo ve-lo yavdil</em>) — bird sin offering technique: the priest wrings the bird's neck incompletely (<em>meliqa</em>), a method unique to bird offerings and distinct from the slaughter (<em>shechita</em>) used for quadrupeds. The blood is then daubed on the altar (v.9) rather than sprinkled or poured as with larger animals.</p>",
    "9": "<p>He shall sprinkle some of the blood of the sin offering on the side of the altar, and the rest of the blood shall be drained out at the base of the altar — the bird's smaller blood volume means only partial sprinkling on the altar side, with the remainder drained at the base; the base-drainage parallels the quadruped sin offering procedure where blood is poured at the altar base after the manipulations (Lev 4:25,30,34).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The second he shall offer as a burnt offering according to the rule — the second bird serves as a burnt offering after the sin offering bird; the pairing (sin offering + burnt offering) from two birds is an economic version of the two-animal offering given by the wealthy person. The sequence sin offering before burnt offering is standard throughout Leviticus (cf. Lev 14:19-20; Num 6:16-17).</p>",
    "11": "<p>But if he cannot afford two turtledoves or two pigeons (<em>im lo taggiya yado lishetei torim</em>), then he who sinned shall bring for his offering a tenth of an ephah of fine flour (<em>issaron solet</em>) for a sin offering — the second tier of graduation: those who cannot afford even two birds bring 1/10 ephah (~2.3 liters) of fine flour. The flour offering without oil or frankincense (v.11b) marks it as penitential rather than celebratory; normal grain offerings include oil (Lev 2:4-7) and frankincense (Lev 2:15).</p>",
    "12": "<p>He shall bring it to the priest, and the priest shall take a handful of it as its memorial portion (<em>azkaratah</em>) and burn this on the altar, on top of the LORD's food offerings — the handful (<em>kometz</em>) burned as the <em>azkarah</em> (memorial portion) is the standard grain offering procedure (Lev 2:2), applied here to the flour chatat. The remainder goes to the priest (v.13). The <em>azkarah</em> (memorial/token) represents the whole offering presented to YHWH; the priestly portion represents the priest's share in the atonement transaction.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Thus the priest shall make atonement for him for the sin that he has committed in any one of these things, and he shall be forgiven. And the remainder shall be for the priest, as in the grain offering — the atonement-and-forgiveness formula is identical whether the person brought a lamb, two birds, or flour; the economic tier does not diminish the efficacy of the atonement. The graduated scale is arguably the most explicitly compassionate provision in the entire sacrificial system, ensuring that poverty is no barrier to atonement.</p>",
    "14": "<p>YHWH spoke to Moses, saying — a new revelation formula separates the guilt offering (asham) legislation (vv.14-19) from the graduated sin offering (vv.1-13). The asham is a distinct sacrifice type from the chatat with different legal triggers and different restitution requirements.</p>",
    "15": "<p>If anyone commits a breach of faith (<em>ma'al</em>) and sins unintentionally in any of the holy things of YHWH (<em>miqdeshei YHWH</em>), he shall bring to YHWH as his compensation (<em>ashmato</em>) a ram without blemish from the flock, valued at silver shekels — the <em>asham</em> is triggered by <em>ma'al</em> (sacrilege, breach of faith against holy things), the failure to give YHWH what is rightly his: tithes, firstfruits, vow payments, priestly dues. The requirement for a ram of silver valuation distinguishes the <em>asham</em> from the <em>chatat</em>; a monetary equivalence must be established, reflecting the reparation (rather than mere atonement) character of the guilt offering.</p>",
    "16": "<p>He shall also make restitution for what he has done amiss in the holy thing and shall add a fifth to it (<em>yosif chamishito alav</em>) and give it to the priest — the <em>chomesh</em> (one-fifth surcharge on restitution) is distinctive to the asham system; no sliding scale applies here because the violation involved specific sacred property with assessable value. In Hammurabi's Code (§§5, 120, 124), restitution requirements vary from two-fold to ten-fold; the Levitical one-fifth surcharge is more modest but applied consistently across all <em>asham</em> contexts. The surcharge goes to the priest as part of the sacred property system.</p>",
    "17": "<p>If anyone sins, doing any of the things that by YHWH's commandments ought not to be done, though he did not know it (<em>ve-hu lo yada</em>), and realizes his guilt (<em>ve-ashem</em>), he shall bear his iniquity — the guilt offering for general unwitting violations (not limited to holy things as in v.15): the person who later realizes they may have transgressed brings the asham as a precautionary measure. This 'floating guilt' concept has no direct ANE parallel; Mesopotamian texts address known violations rather than suspected-but-uncertain ones.</p>",
    "18": "<p>He shall bring to the priest a ram without blemish from the flock, or its equivalent, for a guilt offering. The priest shall make atonement for him for the mistake that he made unintentionally, and he shall be forgiven — the same ram requirement as v.15; the <em>shegagah</em> (error, mistake) term used here and in Lev 4:2 covers the full range of unintentional violations. The asham for unwitting violation in v.17-19 (the 'doubtful asham') was extensively developed in rabbinic law as the <em>asham talui</em> (suspended guilt offering).</p>",
    "19": "<p>It is a guilt offering (<em>asham hu</em>); he has indeed incurred guilt before YHWH — the declaration <em>asham hu</em> formally categorizes the offering and confirms the person's legal status as guilty. The emphatic infinitive absolute pattern (<em>asham asham</em> in the Hebrew sense) reinforces the certainty of guilt even in the case of uncertainty about the specific act.</p>"
  },
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>YHWH spoke to Moses, saying — ch 6 opens a new section with a second revelation formula; in the Hebrew Bible the chapter division begins what rabbinic tradition calls the 'priestly torah' (torat ha-kohanim) section, containing detailed instructions for the priests' execution of each sacrifice type. Vv.1-7 (Heb. 5:20-26) address the asham for interpersonal fraud before returning to the altar-service rubrics.</p>",
    "2": "<p>If anyone sins and commits a breach of faith against YHWH by deceiving his neighbor in a matter of deposit or security (<em>piqqadon o vitesumeth yad</em>), or through robbery, or if he has oppressed his neighbor — the <em>ma'al</em> (breach of faith) category expands here to cover interpersonal wrongs that have a perjury dimension: false denial of a deposit, fraud regarding a pledge, theft, oppression, and false oath. The asham's trigger is the false oath by which the perpetrator invoked YHWH's name to conceal the wrongdoing (v.3), which transforms an interpersonal tort into a sacred violation.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Or has found something lost and lied about it, swearing falsely (<em>nishba al-shaqer</em>) — the false oath is the hinge that connects the interpersonal wrong to YHWH: by swearing falsely in YHWH's name, the offender has made YHWH complicit in the lie, creating a sacrilege dimension that triggers the asham mechanism alongside any civil restitution. The Decalogue's prohibition of false swearing (Exod 20:7) is enacted here through the asham procedure.</p>",
    "4": "<p>If he has sinned and has realized his guilt, he shall restore what he took by robbery or what he got by oppression or the deposit that was committed to him or the lost thing that he found — the sequence of restoration (<em>hashiv</em>) requires returning the specific item or its equivalent; the civil and cultic restoration are inseparable. The rabbinic concept that the stolen item must be returned before the sacrifice is accepted (b. Bava Kamma 94b) derives from this structure.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Or anything about which he has sworn falsely; he shall restore it in full (<em>berosho</em>) and shall add a fifth to it (<em>chomishitav yosif alav</em>), and give it to him to whom it belongs on the day he realizes his guilt — the chomesh (one-fifth surcharge) applies to interpersonal restitution as to sacrilege against holy things (5:16); the surcharge must be delivered on the same day as the acknowledgment of guilt, preventing delay. The precision about timing (day of guilt-realization) reflects the system's concern with the quality of repentance, not merely formal legal compliance.</p>",
    "6": "<p>And he shall bring to the priest as his compensation to YHWH a ram without blemish from the flock, or its equivalent, for a guilt offering — the same ram requirement as Lev 5:15,18; the asham for interpersonal fraud uses the identical animal as the asham for sacrilege against holy things, confirming that false swearing in YHWH's name elevates interpersonal tort into the sacred category. The civil restitution (vv.4-5) and the cultic offering (v.6-7) are both required; neither alone is sufficient.</p>",
    "7": "<p>And the priest shall make atonement for him before YHWH, and he shall be forgiven for any of the things that one may do and thereby become guilty — the comprehensive forgiveness formula: whatever the specific fraud category (robbery, false deposit denial, lost-property fraud, false oath), the atonement mechanism is the same. The breadth of the formula reflects the chatat/asham system's capacity to address the full range of unwitting and acknowledged violations.</p>",
    "8": "<p>YHWH spoke to Moses, saying — the third revelation formula in chs 5–7, introducing the priestly service rubrics for the burnt offering (vv.9-13). These instructions address what the priests do with offerings that have been presented, whereas chs 1–5 address what the offerers present.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Command Aaron and his sons, saying, This is the law (<em>torah</em>) of the burnt offering (<em>olah</em>). The burnt offering shall be on the hearth (<em>al-moqedah</em>) on the altar all night until the morning, and the fire of the altar shall be kept burning on it — the tamid (continual) principle: the <em>olah</em> placed on the altar in the evening must remain burning through the night. The word <em>moqed</em> (hearth, burning-place) describes the altar's fire-bearing surface; the all-night burning allows complete combustion of the evening sacrifice before the morning's ashes are removed.</p>",
    "10": "<p>And the priest shall put on his linen garment (<em>mido bad</em>) and put his linen undergarments on his body, and he shall take up the ashes (<em>deshen</em>) to which the fire has reduced the burnt offering on the altar and put them beside the altar — the priestly linen garments (Exod 28:40-43; Lev 16:4) are required even for the mundane ash-removal; contact with the altar's sacred space demands vestments. The <em>deshen</em> (ashes/fatty remnants) of the burnt offering are treated as sacred residue; they are not simply swept away but placed respectfully beside the altar before being carried outside the camp (v.11).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Then he shall take off his garments and put on other garments and carry the ashes outside the camp to a clean place (<em>makom tahor</em>) — the change of garments for ash-carrying indicates a two-stage holiness gradient: the altar area requires the most sacred garments; the task of carrying ashes outside requires different (lesser?) garments. The <em>makom tahor</em> (clean place) is outside the camp — not the unclean zone where diseased persons and waste are disposed, but a specifically designated clean area for sacred remnants. Later rabbinic law developed the <em>beit ha-deshen</em> (ash-house) from this provision.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The fire on the altar shall be kept burning on it; it shall not go out. The priest shall burn wood on it every morning, and he shall arrange the burnt offering on it and shall burn on it the fat of the peace offerings — the fire's perpetuity (<em>lo tikhbeh</em>, it shall not go out) is stated three times in vv.12-13; the eternal flame is the sign of YHWH's permanent presence and ongoing acceptance of Israel's worship. In the ancient Near East, temple fires were also carefully maintained; the Mesopotamian sacred brazier (<em>dipāru</em>) was kept burning in major temples, but the Levitical emphasis on the fire's divine origin (Lev 9:24) and permanent maintenance is more theologically charged.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Fire shall be kept burning on the altar continually (<em>tamid</em>); it shall not go out — the single word <em>tamid</em> (continually, perpetually) becomes the technical term for all the regular, unending acts of sanctuary service: the <em>olat tamid</em> (continual burnt offering, Exod 29:42), the <em>menorah tamid</em> (continual lamp, Exod 27:20), the <em>lechem ha-panim</em> (bread of presence, displayed continually). The perpetual altar fire is the heartbeat of the sanctuary's operation.</p>",
    "14": "<p>And this is the law of the grain offering (<em>torat ha-minchah</em>). The sons of Aaron shall offer it before YHWH in front of the altar — the grain offering rubric transitions from burnt offering to the <em>minchah</em>; the grain offering can be presented independently (Lev 2) or as an accompaniment to animal sacrifices (Lev 7:11-14; Num 15). The priestly torah for the minchah addresses the handling after presentation: the azkarah burning and the priestly portions.</p>",
    "15": "<p>And one of them shall take from it a handful of the fine flour of the grain offering and of its oil and all the frankincense that is on the grain offering and burn this as its memorial portion (<em>azkaratah</em>) on the altar, a pleasing aroma to YHWH — the <em>kometz azkarah</em> (handful as memorial/token) burns on the altar as the YHWH-portion; the remainder is the priestly food. The term <em>azkarah</em> (memorial, reminder) has generated significant debate: does it remind YHWH of the offerer, or does it serve as the offerer's memorial before YHWH? Both senses may be active.</p>",
    "16": "<p>And the remainder of it Aaron and his sons shall eat. It shall be eaten unleavened (<em>matzot te'achel</em>) in a holy place — priestly eating of the grain offering remainder is a sacred act in a sacred place; the requirement for unleavened (matzot) grain echoes the Passover prohibition on leaven and the general Levitical principle that leaven does not belong in fire-offerings to YHWH (Lev 2:11). The association of leaven with fermentation/corruption may underlie the restriction.</p>",
    "17": "<p>It shall not be baked with leaven. I have given it as their portion from my food offerings. It is most holy (<em>qodesh qedashim hi</em>), like the sin offering and the guilt offering — the category <em>qodesh qedashim</em> (most holy) restricts consumption to male priests only (cf. v.18) within the sanctuary precincts; this is the highest sanctity category in Levitical law, shared by the sin offering (chatat), guilt offering (asham), and grain offering (minchah).</p>",
    "18": "<p>Every male among the children of Aaron may eat of it, as decreed forever throughout your generations, from YHWH's food offerings. Whoever touches them shall become holy (<em>kol asher yigga bahem yiqdash</em>) — the touching-becomes-holy principle: contact with most-holy objects consecrates whatever (whoever) touches them. This is the opposite of impurity transmission; impurity defiles, holiness consecrates. The principle also means that unauthorized touching of most-holy objects would result in dangerous overexposure to holiness — which is why contact is restricted to authorized priests.</p>",
    "19": "<p>YHWH spoke to Moses, saying — a fourth revelation formula introduces the ordination grain offering (<em>minchat chinuch</em>, the offering for Aaron and his sons, vv.20-23).</p>",
    "20": "<p>This is the offering that Aaron and his sons shall offer to YHWH on the day when he is anointed: a tenth of an ephah of fine flour as a regular grain offering, half of it in the morning and half in the evening — the high priest's daily grain offering (minchat chavitin) consists of 1/10 ephah divided into morning and evening portions, offered on a griddle, served fully to YHWH without any priestly retention. This distinguishes the high priest's offering from the lay grain offering (where only the handful burns and priests eat the rest): priestly self-offering is total, not partial.</p>",
    "21": "<p>It shall be made with oil on a griddle (<em>al-machabat bashemen ta'aseh</em>). You shall bring it well mixed, in baked pieces like a grain offering, and offer it for a pleasing aroma to YHWH — the preparation method (griddle with oil) for the daily priestly minchah parallels the lay griddle offering of Lev 2:5; the <em>murcheshet</em> (well-stirred, broken pieces) ensures even cooking. The Talmud (Menachot 78a) reconstructs the distinctive folded-and-griddle-fried preparation of the chavitin.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The anointed priest who is in his place among his sons shall offer it. It is a perpetual due; it shall be wholly burned to YHWH (<em>kalil le-YHWH tiqtár</em>) — every successor high priest continues the father's daily offering; the requirement perpetuates through the priestly genealogy. <em>Kalil</em> (wholly burned, complete) confirms that unlike the lay grain offering (from which priests eat a portion), the priestly grain offering is entirely consumed on the altar — a fitting symbol of priestly self-consecration.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Every grain offering of a priest shall be wholly burned. It shall not be eaten — the prohibition on priestly eating of their own grain offerings parallels the principle that the priests who handle sin offerings cannot eat their own sin offerings (Lev 6:30): the officiating priest cannot be simultaneously the beneficiary of his own sacrificial transaction.</p>",
    "24": "<p>YHWH spoke to Moses, saying — fifth revelation formula; the sin offering (chatat) priestly rubric (vv.25-30) addresses consumption and handling of the most-holy sin offering blood and meat.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Speak to Aaron and his sons, saying, This is the law of the sin offering (<em>torat ha-chatat</em>). In the place where the burnt offering is killed, the sin offering shall be killed before YHWH; it is most holy — the slaughter location (north side of the altar, Lev 1:11) is the same for sin offering and burnt offering, preventing visual distinction between the most-solemn and the standard offerings. The most-holy status means the slaughter space itself is consecrated during the procedure.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The priest who offers it for sin shall eat it. In a holy place it shall be eaten, in the court of the tent of meeting (<em>bachatzer ohel mo'ed</em>) — the sin offering meat is priestly food, consumed within the sanctuary court; the priest who performs the atonement eats the offering, creating a physical identification between the priest and the sin he has borne for the offerer. The eating-as-bearing-sin motif (Lev 10:17: 'you should eat it in the holy place, since it is most holy and was given to you that you may bear the iniquity of the congregation') is explicit in later texts.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Whatever touches its flesh shall be holy, and when any of its blood is sprinkled on a garment, you shall wash that on which it was sprinkled in a holy place — the most-holy garment-staining rule: blood from a sin offering contaminates garments and must be laundered in the sacred precincts (not simply anywhere). The holiness-contamination of the blood (not mere impurity) reflects the concentrated sacred power of the chatat's blood, which has been applied to the altar horns or to the veil in the atoning process.</p>",
    "28": "<p>And the earthen vessel in which it is boiled shall be broken (<em>keli cheres asher tevushal bo yishaver</em>), and if it is boiled in a bronze vessel, that shall be scoured and rinsed in water — the earthenware-vs-bronze distinction for contaminated vessels: earthenware absorbs the sacred residue permanently and must be destroyed; bronze can be cleaned by scouring and rinsing. This distinction appears throughout Leviticus (11:33-34; 14:5,50) as a consistent material-property principle.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Every male among the priests may eat of it; it is most holy — access to sin offering meat is restricted to male priests; female priests' household members and lay Israelites are excluded from this most-holy category (contrast the lesser-holy peace offering portions, which non-priestly household members may eat: Lev 10:14).</p>",
    "30": "<p>But no sin offering shall be eaten from which any blood is brought into the tent of meeting to make atonement in the Holy Place; it shall be burned up with fire — the rule that distinguishes inward-blood-manipulation (vv.30) from outward-blood-manipulation: when the chatat blood is brought inside the tent of meeting (as in Lev 4:3-21 for priests and congregation), the meat is not eaten but burned outside the camp. When the blood is applied only to the outer altar (Lev 4:25-34 for ruler and commoner), the meat is eaten by the priests. The distinction preserves a gradient between the most intense atonement acts (requiring total burning) and the less intense ones (allowing priestly consumption).</p>"
  },
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>This is the law (<em>torah</em>) of the guilt offering (<em>asham</em>). It is most holy — the guilt offering rubric opens ch 7; the most-holy classification places the asham alongside the sin offering and grain offering as restricted to the sanctuary court and male priests. The asham legislation continues from 5:14–6:7, but ch 7 provides the priestly service details (as chs 6–7 do for each sacrifice type).</p>",
    "2": "<p>In the place where they kill the burnt offering they shall kill the guilt offering, and its blood shall be thrown against the sides of the altar all around — the slaughter location (north side, same as burnt offering and sin offering) unifies the most-holy offerings spatially; the blood manipulation for the asham is the <em>zeriqah</em> (throwing/dashing against altar sides) rather than the <em>netinah</em> (applying with finger to altar horns) used for the sin offering. The difference marks the asham as a reparation/restoration offering rather than an atonement-covering offering.</p>",
    "3": "<p>And all its fat shall be offered, the fat tail, the fat that covers the entrails — the fat portions required of the asham are identical to those of the peace offering (Lev 3:3-5,9-10,14-15): tail, covering fat, kidneys, and liver lobe. All fat belongs to YHWH (Lev 3:16) regardless of sacrifice type.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The two kidneys with the fat that is on them at the loins, and the lobe of the liver that he shall remove with the kidneys — the kidney-liver complex that functions as the presumed seat of intellect and emotion in Hebrew anthropology is dedicated to YHWH in every sacrificial animal; the offerer never retains access to these organs. Mesopotamian extispicy (divination from animal entrails) focused on precisely these organs (liver, lungs) as windows to divine will — Levitical legislation redirects them entirely to YHWH's altar, closing them off as sources of illicit divine knowledge.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The priest shall burn them on the altar as a food offering to YHWH; it is a guilt offering — the burning of the fat portions as <em>isheh</em> (food offering by fire) is the YHWH-dedicated portion of the asham, as it is for the burnt and peace offerings. The asham's structure thus includes a YHWH-portion (fat burned), a priest-portion (meat, vv.6-10), but no offerer-portion (unlike the peace offering).</p>",
    "6": "<p>Every male among the priests may eat of it. It shall be eaten in a holy place. It is most holy — asham meat consumption follows sin offering rules (Lev 6:26,29): male priests only, within the sanctuary court. The consistency of most-holy rules across chatat and asham reinforces their shared category as offerings where the priest bears the offerer's guilt through priestly eating.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The guilt offering is just like the sin offering; there is one law for them. The priest who makes atonement with it shall have it — the equivalence formula confirms that chatat and asham share the most-holy priestly-eating rule; the priest who performs the specific atoning ritual has a claim on that offering's meat. This personal stake in the offering by the officiating priest reinforces the depth of priestly identification with the atonement act.</p>",
    "8": "<p>And the priest who offers any man's burnt offering shall have for himself the skin of the burnt offering that he has offered — the burnt offering skin is the officiating priest's perquisite even though the entire animal is consumed on the altar; the skin (hide) is a valuable commodity. Comparative evidence from Mesopotamian temple records (prebend archives from Nippur and Sippar) shows priests received specific portions of temple income, including animal hides — the Levitical system is consistent with the broader ANE priestly prebend system.</p>",
    "9": "<p>And every grain offering baked in an oven and all that is prepared in a pan or on a griddle shall belong to the priest who offers it — the officiating priest keeps the grain offering remainder after burning the <em>azkarah</em>; the method of preparation (oven, pan, griddle) determines the specific priestly ownership claim. The grain offering is explicitly the officiating priest's perquisite, not shared among all the sons of Aaron (contrast the sin offering portions of v.6 where all male priests may eat).</p>",
    "10": "<p>But every grain offering, whether mixed with oil or dry, shall be shared equally among all the sons of Aaron — a distinction between prepared grain offerings (v.9, officiating priest's) and raw/dry grain offerings (v.10, shared equally). The equal distribution of certain priestly portions reflects a deliberate policy of communal priestly economic equity; later developments in the priestly rotation system (1 Chron 24) extended this equity to the weekly service assignments themselves.</p>",
    "11": "<p>And this is the law of the sacrifice of peace offerings (<em>torat zevach ha-shelamim</em>) that one may offer to YHWH — the peace offering (shelamim) rubric is the most elaborate in the chapter because the shelamim has three subtypes (toda, neder, nadavah) with different time limits and specific firstfruit-bread requirements. The shelamim is also the only sacrifice in which the lay offerer retains a portion of the meat.</p>",
    "12": "<p>If he offers it for a thanksgiving (<em>toda</em>), then he shall offer with the thanksgiving sacrifice unleavened loaves mixed with oil, unleavened wafers smeared with oil, and loaves of fine flour well mixed with oil — the toda (thanksgiving) peace offering requires the largest bread accompaniment: three types of unleavened bread plus leavened bread (v.13). The toda is the most festive subcategory; the multiple bread types generate multiple portions distributed to the priests and create a communal meal context.</p>",
    "13": "<p>With the sacrifice of his peace offerings for thanksgiving he shall bring his offering with loaves of leavened bread (<em>chal chametz</em>) — leavened bread accompanies the toda (alone among Levitical offerings); the leaven prohibition applies to offerings burned on the altar, but the bread accompanying the toda is not burned. The leavened loaves are presented as a <em>terumah</em> (contribution) and given to the officiating priest (v.14).</p>",
    "14": "<p>And from it he shall offer one loaf from each offering, as a contribution (<em>terumah</em>) to YHWH. It shall belong to the priest who throws the blood of the peace offerings — the wave/heave offering mechanism: one bread from each type becomes the priestly perquisite through the <em>terumah</em> presentation. The blood-throwing priest (who performed the animal's sacrificial manipulation) receives the bread portion, again linking the officiating role to specific material perquisites.</p>",
    "15": "<p>And the flesh of the sacrifice of his thanksgiving peace offerings shall be eaten on the day of his offering. He shall not leave any of it until the morning (<em>velo yaniach mimenu ad boqer</em>) — the toda's one-day eating limit is the strictest: it must be consumed on the day of sacrifice, with nothing left overnight. This rule ensures the toda remains a genuine communal celebration rather than a family food store; the immediate consumption requirement mirrors the Passover lamb rule (Exod 12:10) and may reflect similar concerns about sacred meat's vulnerability to contamination.</p>",
    "16": "<p>But if the sacrifice of his offering is a vow (<em>neder</em>) or a freewill offering (<em>nadavah</em>), it shall be eaten on the day that he offers his sacrifice, and on the next day what remains of it shall be eaten — vow and freewill peace offerings have a two-day eating window (day of sacrifice + next day), one day more than the toda; the less ceremonially charged context of vow-fulfillment and spontaneous generosity permits the extra day. In the ancient Near East, communal feasting from sacrificed animals was standard practice (Ugaritic dbh texts; Mesopotamian siskur records), but the specific time limits for consumption are a distinctively Israelite regulation.</p>",
    "17": "<p>But what remains of the flesh of the sacrifice on the third day shall be burned up with fire — the three-day/two-day rule terminates with mandatory burning of any remaining meat; the third day is the critical boundary. The same three-day framework appears in the tainted offering (<em>pigul</em>) legislation of Lev 19:7-8; third-day meat is considered ritually void regardless of physical condition.</p>",
    "18": "<p>If any of the flesh of the sacrifice of his peace offering is eaten on the third day, he who offers it shall not be accepted, neither shall it be credited to him. It shall be tainted meat (<em>pigul yihyeh</em>), and the person who eats of it shall bear his iniquity — eating third-day <em>pigul</em> carries personal guilt (<em>avon</em>) for the eater; the offering becomes not merely valueless but actively harmful to eat. The technical term <em>pigul</em> (abomination, voided offering) here applies to peace offerings consumed out of time, as it applies in Lev 19:7 to the original offeror's invalid intent.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Flesh that touches any unclean thing shall not be eaten. It shall be burned up with fire. As for the flesh, everyone who is clean may eat flesh — a second category of peace offering disqualification: contact with impurity voids the meat even within the valid eating window. The principle that sacred meat must remain insulated from impurity sources creates a two-directional protection: the sacrificial meat protects the offerer through the atonement/fellowship mechanism; the community protects the sacred meat through purity maintenance.</p>",
    "20": "<p>But the person who eats of the flesh of the sacrifice of the LORD's peace offerings while an uncleanness is on him, that person shall be cut off (<em>venikhreta</em>) from his people — eating fellowship-offering meat while personally impure triggers <em>karet</em>; the offense is not merely eating tainted food but introducing personal impurity into the sacred communal feast. The severity of the penalty (karet vs. the guilt-bearing of v.18) reflects the distinction between consuming void meat (inadvertent offense) and deliberately eating sacred meat while unclean (presumptuous violation).</p>",
    "21": "<p>And if anyone touches an unclean thing, whether human uncleanness or an unclean beast or any unclean swarming thing, and then eats some flesh from the sacrifice of the LORD's peace offerings, that person shall be cut off from his people — the parallel to v.20 extends the karet penalty to anyone who has contracted impurity from any source (human, animal, insect) and then eats peace-offering meat; all three impurity categories of Lev 11–15 are named, creating comprehensive coverage.</p>",
    "22": "<p>YHWH spoke to Moses, saying — a new revelation formula introduces the fat and blood prohibition (vv.23-27), which provides the legal basis for the brief statements in Lev 3:17 and 17:14.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Speak to the people of Israel, saying, You shall eat no fat of ox or sheep or goat — the fat prohibition is restricted to these three sacrificial species; the fat of game animals (deer, gazelle) may be eaten (Deut 12:15,22; 14:5), since game is never sacrificed. The restriction to sacrificial animals confirms that the fat prohibition is fundamentally about what belongs to YHWH in the cultic sphere, not a dietary rule about fat per se.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The fat of an animal that died of itself (<em>neveilah</em>) and the fat of one that was torn by beasts (<em>terefah</em>) may be put to any other use, but on no account shall you eat it — neveilah (carcass of an animal that died without proper slaughter) and terefah (torn by predator) fat may be used for other purposes (soap, lamp fuel) but not eaten; they are not sacrificeable, so their fat is not YHWH's altar portion, but the holiness-by-association principle keeps them from human consumption. The permitted non-food uses of this fat are consistent with ancient practices of animal rendering for industrial purposes.</p>",
    "25": "<p>For whoever eats of the fat of an animal of which a food offering may be made to YHWH shall be cut off from his people — consuming the sacrificial animals' fat (which belongs to YHWH) triggers karet; the fat reserved for the altar represents YHWH's proprietary claim over the life-sustaining richness of the sacrificial animal. Ancient Near Eastern texts describe gods as receiving the 'fat' of offerings (Gilgamesh Epic, Tablet XI: gods 'gathered like flies' over the sacrifice; the fat and smell are the divine portion), but only Israelite law makes human consumption of that fat a capital offense.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Moreover, you shall eat no blood whatever, whether of fowl or of animal, in any of your dwelling places (<em>bechol moshevoteichem</em>) — the blood prohibition extends to all locations (not only in the sanctuary), to all animal types (fowl and quadruped), and to all Israelites; this universality distinguishes the blood law from the fat law (which applies only to sacrificial species). In Lev 17:10-14 the theological basis is given: blood is the <em>nefesh</em> (life/soul) of the animal; consuming blood would be consuming life itself, which belongs to YHWH.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Whoever eats any blood, that person shall be cut off from his people — karet for blood consumption, as for fat (v.25); the equal penalty level confirms that blood and fat share the same cultic status as belonging definitively to YHWH rather than to human consumers. The blood prohibition is one of the most cross-culturally distinctive markers of Israelite identity in the ancient Near East; it is carried forward in the Jerusalem Council's ruling for Gentile believers (Acts 15:20,29).</p>",
    "28": "<p>YHWH spoke to Moses, saying — a new revelation formula introduces the wave offering (tenupha) and heave offering (terumah) legislation for the peace offering (vv.29-36).</p>",
    "29": "<p>Speak to the people of Israel, saying, Whoever offers the sacrifice of his peace offerings to YHWH shall bring his offering to YHWH from the sacrifice of his peace offerings — the presentation ceremony for peace offerings begins with the offerer bringing specific portions to the priest; the sequence (offerer brings → priest waves/heaves → portions assigned) reflects the shared meal structure of the shelamim, in which YHWH, priest, and offerer all receive portions.</p>",
    "30": "<p>His own hands shall bring the LORD's food offerings. He shall bring the fat with the breast, that the breast may be waved as a wave offering (<em>tenupha</em>) before YHWH — the offerer personally presents the breast and fat together in the waving gesture (<em>tenupha</em>); the waving is a back-and-forth horizontal motion (rabbinic interpretation) that symbolizes presenting the offering to YHWH and receiving it back. The offerer's own hands perform the presentation, maintaining personal involvement even in an increasingly priestly-mediated system.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The priest shall burn the fat on the altar, but the breast shall be for Aaron and his sons — the fat burns on the altar (YHWH's portion); the breast (<em>chazeh ha-tenupha</em>, wave breast) becomes the collective priestly portion shared among all Aaron's sons (v.34). The distinction: fat → YHWH (altar); breast → all priests (shared); right thigh/shoulder → officiating priest (v.33).</p>",
    "32": "<p>And the right thigh (<em>shoq ha-yamin</em>) you shall give to the priest as a contribution (<em>terumah</em>) from the sacrifice of your peace offerings — the right thigh is a heave/contribution offering (<em>terumah</em>), elevated toward YHWH and then given to the officiating priest personally. The distinction between the wave breast (shared among all priests) and the heave thigh (given to the officiating priest) parallels the grain offering distinction of vv.9-10. The thigh/right side preference reflects the common ancient preference for the right side as the place of honor and power.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Whoever among the sons of Aaron offers the blood of the peace offerings and the fat shall have the right thigh for a portion — the blood-offering priest (who performed the blood manipulation) receives the right thigh; this ties the most valuable priestly portion to the most critical priestly action. The priest who bears the greatest ritual responsibility receives the most honorable perquisite.</p>",
    "34": "<p>For the breast that is waved and the thigh that is contributed I have taken from the people of Israel, out of the sacrifices of their peace offerings, and have given them to Aaron the priest and to his sons, as a perpetual due (<em>chok-olam</em>) from the people of Israel — the definitive legal authorization of the priestly food system: YHWH has 'taken' these portions from Israel and 'given' them to the priests as a permanent (<em>olam</em>) entitlement. The legal fiction of divine taking-and-giving grounds the priestly food system in YHWH's sovereign redistribution, not merely human convention.</p>",
    "35": "<p>This is the portion of Aaron and of his sons from the LORD's food offerings, from the day they were presented to serve as priests of YHWH — the closing formula traces the priestly portions to the ordination event (Lev 8–9), grounding the ongoing food-rights in the foundational consecration act. The <em>mishchat aharon umishchat banav</em> (the portion of Aaron and his sons) becomes the technical term for the priestly prebend system authorized here.</p>",
    "36": "<p>YHWH commanded this to be given them by the people of Israel, from the day that he anointed them. It is a perpetual due throughout their generations — the perpetuity formula (<em>chok-olam ledorotam</em>) for the priestly portions concludes the sacrificial law corpus; the same formula is used for the Sabbath (Exod 31:16-17) and for the Passover (Exod 12:17), placing the priestly support system in the same category of permanent covenantal obligations as the most foundational Israelite institutions.</p>",
    "37": "<p>This is the law of the burnt offering, of the grain offering, of the sin offering, of the guilt offering, of the ordination offering, and of the peace offering — the closing summary (<em>zot ha-torah</em>) names all six sacrifice types covered in Lev 6–7: olah, minchah, chatat, asham, millu'im (ordination), shelamim. The summary marks the completion of the priestly rubrics section begun at 6:8 and places all five regular sacrifice types plus the ordination offering under a single coherent legal framework.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Which YHWH commanded Moses on Mount Sinai, on the day that he commanded the people of Israel to bring their offerings to YHWH, in the wilderness of Sinai — the Sinaitic authority formula closes the entire corpus of sacrifice legislation (Lev 1–7): all the offering regulations originate at Sinai, in the wilderness, when YHWH commanded the offerings system into existence. The double location marker (Sinai mountain + Sinai wilderness) anchors the legislation in the specific historical moment of covenant formation.</p>"
  }
}

